    <h2 id="lens">Lens</h2>
    <p>The transparent optical element of the glasses that helps correct vision.</p>

    <h2 id="frame">Frame</h2>
    <p>The structure that holds the lenses in place, available in various materials and styles.</p>

    <h2 id="prescription">Prescription</h2>
    <p>The specific measurements and requirements for vision correction provided by an eye care professional.</p>

    <h2 id="progressive-lenses">Progressive Lenses</h2>
    <p>Lenses that provide a gradual transition between different lens strengths for seeing at varying distances.</p>

    <h2 id="bifocals">Bifocals</h2>
    <p>Lenses that have two distinct optical powers, typically for distance and near vision.</p>

    <h2 id="anti-reflective-coating">Anti-Reflective Coating</h2>
    <p>A coating applied to lenses to reduce glare and reflections, improving vision quality.</p>

    <h2 id="uv-protection">UV Protection</h2>
    <p>A feature that protects the eyes from harmful ultraviolet (UV) rays.</p>

    <h2 id="nose-pads">Nose Pads</h2>
    <p>Small pads that rest on the nose to provide comfort and support for the frame.</p>

    <h2 id="temple">Temple</h2>
    <p>The arm of the glasses that extends from the frame and rests over the ear.</p>

    <h2 id="polarized-lenses">Polarized Lenses</h2>
    <p>Lenses that reduce glare from reflective surfaces, improving visibility and comfort.</p>
